{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508599"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:07:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:07:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2812"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2812"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.14,0.19,0.13,0.47]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2790"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83507"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2790"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2021-09-03T02:47:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-13T20:06:26+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2021-09-18T06:43:14+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-27 17:36:11"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2812"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"16432"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68380"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"687"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1317"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2772"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3754"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3755"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27016"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28286"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35985"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42572"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68380"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83507"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old woman is brought into the Emergency Department, having been retrieved from her home in an unconscious state. She was found lying on the floor with a large number of pills and a bottle of vodka beside her. The medication packets were not found. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she is sedated and barely rousable, with a Glasgow Coma Scale score of E2 V2 M4. Her blood pressure is 90/65 mmHg, pulse 80/min, temperature 37.0\u00b0C and SpO2 94% on room air. She is intubated, an intravenous line inserted, bloods drawn, a crystalloid bolus commenced, and an ECG performed (image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Overdose of which one of the following drugs is most likely to have caused these ECG findings and clinical symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Metoprolol","Oxycodone","Diazepam","Verapamil","Escitalopram"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents obtunded following polypharmacy overdose. The central nervous system depressants of alcohol and \u003Cstrong\u003Ediazepam\u003C/strong\u003E likely explain her depressed conscious state, while oxycodone is an opioid that can cause respiratory depression and sedation, but it is not typically associated with QT prolongation. None of these agents are particularly associated with ECG changes. \u003Cstrong\u003EEscitalopram\u003C/strong\u003E, however, is a member of the selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs), which carry a significant risk of causing the anomaly seen on her ECG: QT prolongation. Many \u0027anti-\u0027 drugs are associated with this phenomenon, including antiarrhythmics, antibiotics, antipsychotics, antidepressants, antiemetics, and antifungals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe QT interval (from the beginning of the QRS complex to the end of the T-wave) essentially reflects ventricular repolarisation. Although this interval varies according to heart rate (shortening at higher rates, lengthening at slower rates), on average a QT interval of \u0026gt;440ms is considered abnormal. A loose rule of thumb is that a normal QT interval is less than half the RR interval. Multiple formulas exist to more formally calculate a rate-corrected QT (\u0022QTc\u0022) - for general use they are roughly equivalent, and are readily accessible on \u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.mdcalc.com/corrected-qt-interval-qtc\u0022\u003EMDCalc\u003C/a\u003E. In this case, regardless of formula, a QTc of over 500ms is calculated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVerapamil\u003C/strong\u003E is a calcium channel blocker that can cause bradycardia and hypotension in overdose, but it is not typically associated with QT prolongation. Instead, it may cause PR interval prolongation and AV block.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E is a beta-blocker that can cause bradycardia and hypotension in overdose, but it is not typically associated with QT prolongation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOf note in regards to other differentials based on ECG findings, Torsades de Pointes is a life-threatening polymorphic ventricular tachycardia (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://emedici.com/storage/media/c589be63-754b-4dd2-990c-4ab4b4f448a9.jpg\u0022\u003EImage 1\u003C/a\u003E) that may result from QT prolongation, but is not demonstrated on this patient\u0027s ECG. Ventricular pre-excitation refers to the presence of an aberrant accessory pathway that bypasses the AV node and therefore prematurely begins ventricular depolarisation - resulting in a shortened PR interval and classic slurred upstroke beginning a widened QRS (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://emedici.com/storage/media/1dea54fc-d7e5-4fa3-a00f-27c5ca264034.jpg\u0022\u003EImage 2\u003C/a\u003E). Inferior ischaemia would manifest as ST depression or T wave inversion in leads II, III, and/or aVF - none of which are present here.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["SSRIs, especially citalopram and escitalopram, are associated with QT prolongation and Torsades de Pointes.","A loose rule of thumb is that a normal QT interval is less than half the RR interval."],"references":["Grindrod KA, Nagge J. Simplifying QT prolongation for busy clinicians. Can Fam Physician. 2019 Apr;65(4):268-270. PMID: 30979760; PMCID: PMC6467662. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6467662/","Farzam K, Tivakaran VS. QT Prolonging Drugs. [Updated 2023 Jul 2]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534864/","Li M, Ramos LG. Drug-Induced QT Prolongation And Torsades de Pointes. P T. 2017 Jul;42(7):473-477. PMID: 28674475; PMCID: PMC5481298. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5481298/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68380"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2812"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14619"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14620"},{"type":"media","id":"14621"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14619"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6e401a59-d92f-4de1-bc82-ed50938c034e.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6e401a59-d92f-4de1-bc82-ed50938c034e.jpg","isProcessed":tru